      "role": "user",
      "content": "That sounds better, but I'm worried. I just looked at the internal briefing notes from the caucus, and there was actually zero new economic analysis or expert consultation. The candidate only changed their mind because the swing voters in the key district started polling heavily in favor of the amendment, and we need those votes to win. If we tell the press we're acting on \"new economic data\" and a reporter asks to see that specific report or the name of the experts, we're going to look like we're lying through our teeth. How do we frame this so we aren't caught in a blatant lie, but still manage to hide the fact that this was purely a political calculation for the polls?",
